mily Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Scottish:  see  Semple  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Semple","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): nickname from Middle English, Older Scots, and Old French <i>simple</i> ‘simple, straightforward, humble’ (from Latin <i>simplus</i>). The Scottish name was taken to Ulster in the 17th century, and a Scottish family of this name held the hereditary post of Sheriff of Renfrewshire from the 13th century.","English: variant of   Sample  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Sempill 1st of Largs was born about 1270, in Renfrewshire, Scotland, his father, Chevalier, Baron d' Esneval Robert d' ESNEVAL \"Sempill\" Chevalier, Baron d' Esneval seigneur de Pavilly\", was 22 and his mother, Mrs. Robert Sempill, was 23. He died before 1330, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1270–before 1330":"umbes 1270–enne 1330","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1271–Male":"1271–Surnud","1287–Female":"1287–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud